Huffman Coding Text File Encoder and Decoder
Purpose Statement
The purpose of this project is to create a Huffman Coding program using C++. The program can
encode and decode text files. Huffman Coding is used in computer science to reduce file size by using
shorter binary codes for characters that appear more often.
Introduction and Background
Data compression is important because it helps save storage and makes files smaller. Huffman Coding
is a compression algorithm that uses binary trees and frequency counting. Characters that appear
many times get shorter binary codes, while rare characters get longer codes.
Implementation
This project was implemented in C++. The program reads text from input.txt. An unordered_map was
used to count character frequencies. A priority queue (min heap) was used to build the Huffman Tree.
The program generates binary codes and stores the encoded message in encoded.txt. The decoded
text is stored in decoded.txt.
Results and Analysis
The program successfully encoded and decoded the text file. The decoded output matched the original
input. The project demonstrated the use of heaps, binary trees, hash maps, and file input/output.
Conclusion and Future Work
This project successfully implemented Huffman Coding using C++. In the future, the program could
support larger files and real binary compression.
